&quot;The bottle was wired tightly between two horseshoes to facilitate its breakage while also symbolizing good luck.&quot; 

After four failed swings (two by Masson, two by Porte) the bottle slipped out of its horseshoe sling and rolled on the ground...&quot;As a last resort, the bottle was trussed to the prow and Porte grimly assaulted it with a sledgehammer. Both the hull and Porte's wearing apparel were doused with foaming champagne, to the 'considerable merriment' of the onlookers.&quot;
from &quot;Glenn Curtiss, Pioneer of Flight,&quot; by C.R. Roseberry. Syracuse University Press, 1972. p.373-74
